catPose.description: This pose stretches the back torso and provides a gentle massage to the spine and belly organs.

easyPose.description: Don't let the name fool you. If you're used to sitting in chairs, Easy Pose or Sukhasana can be quite challenging. This pose calms the brain, strengthens the back and stretches the knees and ankles.

cowPose.description: Cow Pose is an easy, gentle way to warm up the spine, it stretches the front torso and neck. It also provides a gentle massage to the spine and belly organs.

chairPose.description: The chair pose works the muscles of the arms and legs, it stretches the ankles, thighs, calves spine, chest, and shoulders. It also stimulates the diaphragm and heart.

heroPose.description: The hero pose is a balm for tired legs at the end of the day, as well as an alternative to Lotus for seated meditation. It helps strengthen the thighs, knees, ankles, and arches while also helping to improve digestion and relieve gas.

cobraPose.description: The cobra pose, fights fatigue and relieves lower back pain, boosting both the energetic and the physical body, it strengthens the spine, chest, lungs, shoulders and abdomen while also soothing sciatica and stimulating abdominal organs.

highLungePose.description: The high lunge pose counteracts the effects of modern-day sitting syndrome by lengthening your hip flexors, stretching the groin, and strengthening your legs and arms.

extendedSideAnglePose.description: The extended side angle pose helps you find length in your side body. It strengthens and stretches the legs, knees, waist, chest and shoulders among others. It also stimulates abdominal organs and increases stamina.

halfLordOfTheFishesPose.description: The half lord of the fishes pose invites and energy in the spine that helps to stimulate proper digestion while improving postural and body awarness. It stimulates the liver and kidneys, energizes the spine,  and stretches the shoulders, hips, and neck.

halfMoonPose.description: The half moon pose provides leg and ankle strength, stretches the groin, hamstrings, calves, shoulders and chest. It also improves coordination and helps relieve stress.

revolvedSideAnglePose.description: This revolved variation of Utthita Parsvakonasana requires a lot of flexibility to twist so deeply and ground the back heel. It helps with increasing taming and improving balance as well as strengthening and stretching the legs, knees, ankles, chest and spine.

noosePose.description: In the noose pose, the arms are wrapped around the squatting legs and the hands are clasped behind the back, forming a "noose". This pose stretches and strengthens the ankles, thighs, groins and spine. It also stimulates the abdominal organs and improves overall posture.

fireLogPose.description: The fire log pose stretches the outer hips intensely, particularly the piriformis, which is often the main culprit of sciatic pain. This pose helps with stretching out the hip and groins.

extendedHandToBigToePose.description: The extended hand to big toe pose aids in strengthening and stretching the legs and ankles. It also improves the overall sense of balance.

eaglePose.description: You need strength, flexibility, endurance, and unwavering concentration for the eagle pose. This pose helps in strengthening and stretching the ankles, calves, hips, shoulders, and upper back. It also improves concentration and overall sense of balance.

bigToePose.description: This pose gently lengthens and strengthens even stubbornly tight hamstrings. It also aids in relieving headaches and stress while calming the brain and improving digestion.

craneCrowPose.description: A compact arm balance, crane pose/crow pose, called Bakasana in Sanskrit, encourages toning in the abs and the arms, strengthening in the core, and improves focus in the mind. It also stretches the upper back and opens the groins.

handStandPose.description: The downward hand stand pose helps in boosting the body's energy and building confidence in the mind. It also boosts energy, improves boddy awarness, and strengthens the core, back, shoulders, thighs, and buttocks.

lordOfTheDancePose.description: Nataraja is another name for Shiva and his dance symbolizes cosmic energy. Natarajasana, or Lord of the dance pose. This pose helps in stretching out the shoulders, chest, thighs, groins, and abdomen. It also improves overall balance.

sideRecliningLegLiftPose.description: This side-reclining pose stretches the backs of the legs, the sides of the torso, and tones the belly.

fireFlyPose.description: Want to fly? Fire up your core. Firefly pose is an arm balance pose that requires more core strength than arm strength. It tones the belly, improves the sense of balance, and strengthens the arms and wrists.

sageKoundinyaIIPose.description: A pose dedicated to the Sage Koundinya II. This pose, tones the belly and spine, strengthens the arms and wrists, and gives your self-confidence a big boost.

shoulderPressingPose.description: This arm balance relies more on precise positioning than on strength, making it more accessible for students beginning an arm balancing practice.

lotusPose.description: Lotus pose, or Padmasana in Sanskrit, requires open hips and consistent practice. This pose creates an essential foundation for meditation practice while helping to manage stress with a conscious stretch in the front of the thighs and ankles.

peacockPose.description: The peacock pose, called Mayurasana in Sanskrit, works to lovingly strengthen the core while stretching the palm side of the wrists, the wrists flexors, which counteracts the effects of typing.

sageKoundinyaIPose.description: This pose dedicated to the Sage Koundinya I has a lot going on—the twist, the legs going their separate ways, oh, and the arm balance. It helps strengthening the arms and wrists while toning the belly and spine at the same time.

upwardFacingTwoFootStaffPose.description: Can you practice the headstand pose without strain? Then, you're ready. This pose stretches the entire front body and opens the chest.
